# 📝 Rails + PostgreSQL Schema Sanity Checklist

1️⃣ Initial Setup

 Decide if you need a custom schema (multi-tenant, logical separation, or just experimenting)

 Add a migration to create the schema:

class CreateCustomSchema < ActiveRecord::Migration[8.1]
  def up
    execute "CREATE SCHEMA IF NOT EXISTS my_schema"
  end

  def down
    execute "DROP SCHEMA IF EXISTS my_schema CASCADE"
  end
end


 Set schema_search_path in database.yml:

development:
  schema_search_path: my_schema,public

test:
  schema_search_path: my_schema,public

2️⃣ Table Creation

 Create tables inside the schema:

create_table "my_schema.users" do |t|
  t.string :name
  t.timestamps
end


 Or rely on search_path and unqualified names; tables will go into the first schema in the path.

3️⃣ Migrations & Database Rebuild

 Use rails db:migrate instead of db:schema:load for custom schemas

 If resetting DB, drop and recreate before running migrations:

rails db:drop
rails db:create
rails db:migrate


 Verify schema exists:

\dn         -- lists schemas
\dt my_schema.*  -- lists tables
## To set custom schema:
```
SET search_path TO utech;
```

4️⃣ schema.rb vs structure.sql

 Empty schemas will not appear in schema.rb

 If you need full fidelity (including empty schemas, triggers, views, functions):

# config/application.rb
config.active_record.schema_format = :sql


 Dump structure:

rails db:structure:dump

5️⃣ Common Pitfalls
Issue	Cause	Fix
Schema missing in schema.rb	Empty schema / not referenced	Create at least one table OR use :sql format
Tables still in public	Default search_path	Set schema_search_path to include custom schema
Migration shows “up” but schema missing	db:schema:load / schema.rb used to recreate DB	Re-run migration or rebuild DB with db:migrate
6️⃣ Environment & Team

 Ensure schema_search_path is consistent across development, test, and production

 Include migration and DB reset instructions in README

 Keep pitfalls and notes in docs/pitfalls/database-pitfalls.md

✅ Following this checklist will make your custom schemas behave consistently across all environments and Rails versions.